This complaint is directed solely at the woman at the cash register around noon today (I'll be generous and assume this was her first day on the job?) and whomever is responsible for training her.  I enter and am looking at the board from a good distance away. The very rude woman in question says, "Hi, whaddya want?" I say I don't know yet, and the woman walks away without further comment. A minute later, I move up to the front of the cash register, and after a while I hear a disembodied voice say, "Whaddya want?" Looking around, I see no one, but finally see literally ONE EYE of this woman, who has moved several feet away and is standing behind a row of coffee machines. Because of how quietly she asked the question, and because I can only see one eye through all the machinery, I have no idea if she was speaking to me, so I ask, "Are you talking to me?" to which she turns to her co-workers and snidely says "No, I'm talking to Jesus Christ."  Having rarely experienced such open contempt for a customer, I just sort of shake my head disbelievingly. (And I'm not religious, but some might have been bothered by her language.) At this point, the woman actually comes out to the register, where I can see her. I order a bagel and a small hot chocolate. She is dismissive of me throughout the entire encounter, attempting to put in the information as quickly as possible, but that only results in a series of errors. First she puts in an order for just a bagel, and then enters that I've paid with a $20 cash and proceeds to print the receipt, when in fact I haven't even been given a total or taken my wallet out yet.  She then says to me, "What you paying with, card?" and I say, "Well, I was going to pay with this $5." She promptly ignores me and calls some other unfortunate co-workers over so they can correct her mistake. They're all trying to figure this out and she re-enters the order, this time remembering to add the hot chocolate, but doesn't remember what size I asked for and says, "What kind of hot chocolate you want? Small? Large?" I say again, "Small," but ALREADY she's talking to another coworker, and doesn't hear my response. She then turns to me again and rudely says, "What SIZE?" and I repeat, "Small." At this point there's 3 or so people up by the register trying to fix her error, so I say, "If it'll help, I can pay with card," but this woman is not paying attention to me (and clearly hasn't from the beginning) and says nothing.  Finally the transaction is complete, but from beginning to end this woman demonstrated nothing but contempt for me and is clearly incapable of working the cash register. It is one thing to be incompetent, it's another entirely to be unapologetically incompetent.  I don't understand how anyone can work in the food industry and treat customers like a joke, especially in front of their face. It was the Jesus Christ comment that upset me the most. The experience left me so frustrated, that I'm ashamed to admit that, after receiving my order I loudly said, "You are TERRIBLE at your job!" and left the building. I truly am ashamed for having raised my voice, I should have asked to speak to a manager. This was not the mature way to respond.  I hope management can help this employee behave with some shred of decency towards customers, (and for my part, I will attempt to react to incredibly poor customer service in a more appropriate fashion in the future).
